    "narrative": "For LawDog\u2019s lineup today, **Cal Raleigh** (70.13) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (69.13) emerge as our primary offensive engines. **Cal Raleigh** benefits significantly from a favorable park factor and a premium #2 slotting against Liberatore, while **Geraldo Perdomo**\u2019s elite lead-off deployment against a vulnerable 5.26 xERA from M\u00e1rquez makes him a high-floor selection for run production. Meanwhile, **Jonathan Aranda** (63.78) is a mandatory start due to a strong platoon advantage against Ober; his refined plate discipline and 0.382 xwOBA suggest he is positioned to capitalize on the 12% boost provided by the R-on-R matchup profile.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved our utility and bench spots. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (59.86) remains in the lineup despite a challenging matchup against Gausman, as his foundational skill set overrides the negative BvP data. **Jeremiah Jackson** (45.71) serves as our most notable bench exclusion, falling just short of the 50-point threshold; while the park factor in his matchup against Crochet is appealing, the 2.86 xERA of the opposing starter introduces too much volatility compared to the high-efficiency platoon edges provided by **Bryson Stott** (66.28) and **Taylor Ward** (59.23). \n\nWe are monitoring two specific risks today. First, our exposure to Eury P\u00e9rez (3.80 xERA) is high, affecting **Luis Arraez**, **Matt Chapman**, **Jung Hoo Lee**, and **Drew Gilbert**. While the wind blowing out and the high SB potential against a slow-delivering arm provide a mathematical cushion, the quality of the opposing arm keeps these scores in the mid-50s or lower. Finally, **Taylor Ward** faces a significant test against Crochet; although the park factors inflate his score to 59.23, the elite nature of the opposing pitcher makes this a \"marginal\" play where we are banking on his leadoff efficiency to sustain our daily category targets.",
